The need for an accurate and reliable prediction of the hourly load demand is an important aspect of system management [2] for:

•scheduling functions: generator unit commitment, hydrothermal coordination, short term maintenance, fuel allocation, power interchange, transaction evaluation [3];
•network analysis functions: dispatcher power flow, optimal power flow [3].

 The fixed point \${\bf p}={\rm r}({\rm R}^{\ast}, {\bf p})\$ is unique if the correspondence \${\rm r}({\rm R}^{\ast}, {\bf p})\$ is a \$standard\$ function [20], i.e., if it satisfies the following properties:

a.positivity: \${\bf r}({\bf R}^{\ast}, {\bf p})>0\$;
b.monotonicity: if \${\bf p}>{\bf p}^{\prime}\$, then \${\rm r}({\rm R}^{\ast}, {\bf p})>{\rm r}({\rm R}^{\ast}, {\bf p}^{\prime})\$;
c.scalability: for all \$\mu>1, \mu {\rm r}({\rm R}^{\ast}, {\bf p})>{\rm r}({\rm R}^{\ast}, \mu {\bf p})\$.
